}}Bay Shore, Michigan, is a small [[Census-designated place|Census-Designated Place]] (CDP) with a current population of 607 people as of the 2023.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Census profile: Bay Shore, MI|url=http://censusreporter.org/profiles/16000US2606180-bay-shore-mi/|website=Census Reporter|access-date=2025-11-28|language=en}}</ref>

The community is characterized by an older demographic, with a median age of 51.3 years, which is significantly higher than the median age for the state of [[Michigan]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|title=Bay Shore, MI {{!}} Data USA|url=https://datausa.io/profile/geo/bay-shore-mi/|website=datausa.io|access-date=2025-11-28|language=en}}</ref>

The population is predominantly [[White people|White]], with approximately 91% identifying as White (Non-[[Hispanic]]).<ref name=":0" />

Socioeconomically, Bay Shore demonstrates higher figures than the state average, featuring a median household income of $72,538.<ref name=":1" /> This represents a 12.6% increase from the previous year, when the median income was $64,444.<ref name=":1" /> 

The community's poverty rate is 9.3%, which is lower than the Michigan state rate of 13.1%.<ref name=":0" /> The homeownership rate is quite high at 91.1%, and 92.6% of residents have a high school degree or higher.<ref name=":0" />

The population saw a notable 13.9% increase between 2022 and 2023, growing from 533 to 607 residents.<ref name=":1" /> The median property value in the CDP was $116,300 in 2023. Most employed residents commute by driving alone (55%), with a significant portion carpooling (40%), and the average commute time is 16.6 minutes.<ref name=":0" /> 

